      Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, back Monday.Much =
efficient very marketLook I enjoyed  GameStop as much as anyone. It was dum=
b fun, it seemed to say something weird and  alarming but not=C2=A0too=C2=
=A0serious about financial capitalism, nobody got too badly hurt, it had so=
me good characters, it kept us entertained for a while.  Non-fungible  toke=
ns are  exasperating,  but in an  interesting way. I thought  the deli was =
pretty good. Financial news in 2021 is incredibly stupid, sure, but I can t=
ake pleasure in it.But Dogecoin =E2=80=A6=C2=A0man, I don=E2=80=99t object =
to Dogecoin; the basic thing of =E2=80=9CDogecoin is a parody of Bitcoin th=
at is now worth a lot of money=E2=80=9D is fine, that=C2=A0is=C2=A0funny, f=
ine fine fine. It=E2=80=99s just, I mean,  here=E2=80=99s a whole article o=
f this stuff:A potential trigger for the latest leg up: Tesla Inc. co-found=
er and crypto fan Elon Musk is appearing on Saturday Night Live this weeken=
d, spurring speculation he may talk up Dogecoin again on the comedy show.=
=E2=80=9CWhen you think about the full spirit of what this crypto revolutio=
n is, there=E2=80=99s something pure in what Dogecoin has done,=E2=80=9D Mi=
ke Novogratz, founder of Galaxy Digital Holdings, said on CNBC. =E2=80=9CI =
worry that once the enthusiasm rolls out, there are no developers, there=E2=
=80=99s no institutions coming in. But it=E2=80=99s got the moniker of the =
people=E2=80=99s coin right now and it=E2=80=99d be very dangerous to be sh=
ort.=E2=80=9DThe overnight gain took Dogecoin=E2=80=99s one-week advance to=
 118% and its value to $87 billion in Wednesday trading, according to CoinM=
arketCap.com data, eclipsing the largest exchange-traded gold fund and even=
 stocks like Fedex Corp. and Snap Inc. A year ago, the asset was worth just=
 $315 million. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CAt some point, something is just real,=E2=
=80=9D said Sam Bankman-Fried, the Hong Kong-based chief executive officer =
of the FTX crypto exchange. =E2=80=9CIf Dogecoin is stupid and valueless, i=
t shouldn=E2=80=99t be worth $90 billion. How about gold or Bitcoin or euro=
s? Our collective imagination has given them value, and now we just think a=
bout them having value.=E2=80=9DDogecoin, started in 2013 as a joke based o=
n the Shiba Inu breed of dog, may become so accepted by the mainstream it m=
ight evolve into a payment option at retailers, Bankman-Fried said. At Bloc=
kfolio, a firm owned by FTX that helps users manage their crypto portfolios=
, trading volumes are spiking with Dogecoin=E2=80=99s every gain, a sign it=
=E2=80=99s become essential to the whole ecosystem. ...While it=E2=80=99s d=
ifficult to assign firm reasons to Dogecoin=E2=80=99s ascent, a few factors=
 have fueled the gains. On April 20, a day normally associated with pot, so=
me users got #DogeDay trending to push up the price. Celebrities from Musk =
to the Dallas Mavericks=E2=80=99 billionaire owner Mark Cuban also jumped o=
n the bandwagon. The Gemini crypto exchange backed by the Winklevoss twins =
announced Tuesday it will soon enable trading of the coin.Just imagine trav=
eling 10 years back in time and trying to explain=C2=A0this to someone; jus=
t imagine what an idiot you=E2=80=99d feel like. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s g=
oing to be this online currency that people think is a form of digital gold=
, and then there=E2=80=99s going to be a different=C2=A0online currency tha=
t is a parody of the first one based on a meme about a talking Shiba Inu, a=
nd that one will have a market capitalization bigger than 80% of the compan=
ies in the S&P 500, and its value will=C2=A0fluctuate based on things like =
who is hosting =E2=80=98Saturday Night Live=E2=80=99 and whether people twe=
et a hashtag about it on the pot-joke holiday, and Bloomberg will write art=
icles and banks will write research notes about those sorts of catalysts, a=
nd it will remain a perfectly=C2=A0ridiculous content-free parody even as p=
eople properly take it completely seriously because there are billions of d=
ollars at stake.=E2=80=9DFor that matter, imagine being me, now, and trying=
 to say something interesting about this; just imagine what an idiot I feel=
 like.=C2=A0I hope Elon Musk is funny on SNL! That will make the value of D=
ogecoin go up! Me, I want to write about dynamic=C2=A0hedging of inverse ex=
change-traded notes on volatility indexes, but that=E2=80=99s not how finan=
ce works anymore. =E2=80=9CDon't forget to pencil in the SNL opening as a k=
ey market event risk for next week,=E2=80=9D tweeted Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Tr=
acy Alloway.In the last=C2=A0dumb, dumb year I have proposed two very dumb =
theories of financial markets, both of which seem relevant to Dogecoin:=09T=
he   boredom markets hypothesis says that people will buy stocks when buyin=
g stocks is more fun than other things they could be doing for fun.=09The  =
 Elon markets hypothesis says =E2=80=9Cthat things are valuable not based o=
n their cash flows but on their proximity to Elon Musk.=E2=80=9DAre those h=
ypotheses self-limiting in some way? The point of the BMH (boredom markets =
hypothesis) was that as pandemic lockdowns eased, people would go back to d=
oing things that are actually fun, and spend less time day-trading stocks. =
But I did not fully reckon with the possibility that people would spend the=
 pandemic lockdowns not just trading stocks, but also=C2=A0making it more f=
un to trade stocks. Partly that is by making the trading experience more fu=
n and social, with Reddit boards and sea chanteys to make your favorite sto=
ck a bit more exciting. Partly it is by finding more fun things to trade th=
an stocks; why buy Tesla Inc. stock when you can buy an imaginary coin name=
d after a Shiba Inu meme that Elon Musk will tout on =E2=80=98Saturday Nigh=
t Live=E2=80=99? Partly it is just through the traditional way that trading=
 is sometimes fun:=C2=A0Everything keeps going up, so it is fun to buy the =
things because you make money.I suppose the boredom-driven rally ends throu=
gh some combination of (1) people can do normal fun things again and (2) li=
ke, Dogecoin drops for fundamental reasons (?) and it stops being free mone=
y all the time?The point of the E'MH (E-prime MH, Elon markets hypothesis, =
to distinguish it from the efficient markets hypothesis, which owns the rig=
hts to =E2=80=9CEMH=E2=80=9D) is not too dissimilar: Elon Musk combines the=
 concepts of =E2=80=9Cget rich=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chave fun=E2=80=9D in a=
n unusual way. I once  wrote:Musk is the richest person in the world, and i=
n a dynamic, fun, traveling-to-Mars sort of way. It makes sense that his pr=
onouncements have a certain religious character, that his tweets can endow =
arbitrary objects with mana. If the richest person in the world tweets =E2=
=80=9CGamestonk!=E2=80=9D then I think that means that, if you buy GameStop=
 stock, you will partake in his wealth and dynamism at a remove; you will g=
et rich and have fun doing it. (Not! Investing! Advice!)=C2=A0Again, when h=
is advice stops working to make people rich, or when there are more fun thi=
ngs to do, this effect should lessen. Also I just can=E2=80=99t imagine thi=
s schtick working forever? Even if he keeps doing funny things, the cumulat=
ive effect is sort of deadening; his 1,000th bizarre tweet is going to be l=
ess funny than his first.=C2=A0Here is a 22-page research note about Dogeco=
in. An excerpt:Dogecoin is a codebase fork of Luckycoin, which itself was a=
 codebase fork of Junkcoin, which was a codebase fork of Litecoin, which in=
 turn is a codebase fork of Bitcoin. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0[Founder Jackson] Palme=
r commented that =E2=80=9Cinitially we thought it would just make the viral=
 rounds on social media, attract a few miners for fun and then slow down. B=
ut something really interesting happened =E2=80=94=C2=A0it went from being =
a humorous take on cryptocurrency to actually driving mainstream awareness =
of the topic.=E2=80=9DThat=E2=80=99s sort of profound, isn=E2=80=99t it? Ba=
sically the way things work is:=09Assets trade among participants in some n=
iche market; that niche might be early-adopter crypto enthusiasts or Reddit=
 traders=C2=A0or  alumni of the wrestling team at a New Jersey high school =
or whatever you want. The assets have prices that may or may not make sense=
 to=C2=A0you, but that make sense to people within the niche.=09Some event =
causes one asset in the niche ecosystem to break out into the public consci=
ousness: One joke cryptocurrency is really funny, one Reddit meme stock is =
really funny, one stock traded by the New Jersey wrestlers is really funny,=
 etc. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s really funny=E2=80=9D seems to be essential her=
e: The way to attract=C2=A0mainstream attention to some niche asset is most=
ly by making the mainstream laugh.=09The mainstream attention attracts buye=
rs: People say =E2=80=9Coh that thing is funny, and it=E2=80=99s specifical=
ly funny that it is a traded asset with a high price, I should buy it.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0=09So the price for that one funny asset shoots up until it doe=
sn=E2=80=99t make sense to anyone.On this theory, Dogecoin=E2=80=99s status=
 as a joke is what makes it valuable. Litecoin is sort of the original fork=
 of Bitcoin, the more sensible and serious parent of Dogecoin, the second-b=
est Bitcoin as it were. It has a=C2=A0total market cap of about $23 billion=
 now. Being the second-best Bitcoin is sort of meh. Being the=C2=A0funny=C2=
=A0Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0the hilariously=C2=A0worst=C2=A0Bitcoin, even =E2=
=80=94 gets attention, and attention is the most valuable thing in the worl=
d.Number too bigThis is the best rationale I=E2=80=99ve ever seen for a sto=
ck split:Berkshire Hathaway Inc. is trading at more than $421,000 per Class=
 A share, and the market is optimistic. That=E2=80=99s a problem.The price =
has grown so high, it has nearly hit the maximum number that can be stored =
in one common way exchange computers handle digits.On Tuesday, Nasdaq Inc. =
temporarily suspended broadcasting prices for Class A shares of Berkshire o=
ver several popular data feeds. Such feeds provide real-time price updates =
for a number of online brokerages and finance websites.Nasdaq=E2=80=99s com=
puters can only count so high because of the compact digital format they us=
e for communicating prices. The biggest number they can handle is $429,496.=
7295. Nasdaq is rushing to finish an upgrade later this month that would fi=
x the problem.It isn=E2=80=99t just Nasdaq. Another exchange operator, IEX =
Group Inc., said in March that it would stop accepting investors=E2=80=99 o=
rders in Class A shares of Berkshire Hathaway =E2=80=9Cdue to an internal p=
rice limitation within the trading system.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6Here=E2=80=99s=
 the trouble: Nasdaq and some other market operators record stock prices in=
 a compact computer format that uses 32 bits, or ones and zeros. The bigges=
t number possible is two to the 32nd power minus one, or 4,294,967,295. Sto=
ck prices are frequently stored using four decimal places, so the highest p=
ossible price is $429,496.7295.No other stock is anywhere near Berkshire Cl=
ass A=E2=80=99s stratospheric price levels, so it is understandable why the=
 engineers behind Nasdaq=E2=80=99s and IEX=E2=80=99s systems chose the numb=
er format, which programmers call a four-byte unsigned integer.When I first=
 read the headline (=E2=80=9CBerkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s Stock Price Is To=
o Much for Computers=E2=80=9D) I assumed that this was a=C2=A0signed=C2=A0i=
nteger, and that if Berkshire=E2=80=99s price ever ticked up to $429,496.72=
96 it would roll over to be some enormous negative number in the exchanges=
=E2=80=99 computer systems. And then if you put in a market order to sell B=
erkshire when you saw it trading at $429,496.70, it would take a second to =
get a fill, and in that second the price would tick over to=C2=A0like negat=
ive $429,400, and the exchange would say =E2=80=9Cokay we have taken away y=
our Berkshire share and you owe us $429,400,=E2=80=9D and oops oops oops.Bu=
t, no, unsigned. I guess it rolls over to zero? Also great fun. =E2=80=9CWo=
w, Berkshire is really going up, I should sell,=E2=80=9D you think, as it h=
its $429,495, and then by the time your order goes in it has rolled over an=
d you sell for two cents. Too slow! Honestly the stock market should work l=
ike that. Stock prices get too high and just start over at zero. Keep thing=
s interesting.My model for the last year or so in the capital markets has b=
een =E2=80=9Ceverything keeps getting a little dumber each day,=E2=80=9D bu=
t what if this story is actually the better model? What if the correct mode=
l is something like =E2=80=9Ccapital markets kept getting more and more per=
fect until they reached maximum perfection sometime in=C2=A02020 and then, =
due to a glitch in the number formatting, flipped over into absolute nonsen=
se=E2=80=9D?


