ic2hhcmU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa1fd034d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">best rationale</a> I=E2=80=99ve ever seen=
 for a stock split:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Berkshire H=
athaway Inc. is trading at more than $421,000 per Class A share, and the ma=
rket is optimistic. That=E2=80=99s a problem.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The price has grown so high, it has nearly hit the maximum number that c=
an be stored in one common way exchange computers handle digits.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Tuesday, Nasdaq Inc. temporarily suspended broadca=
sting prices for Class A shares of Berkshire over several popular data feed=
s. Such feeds provide real-time price updates for a number of online broker=
ages and finance websites.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nasdaq=E2=80=99s=
 computers can only count so high because of the compact digital format the=
y use for communicating prices. The biggest number they can handle is $429,=
496.7295. Nasdaq is rushing to finish an upgrade later this month that woul=
d fix the problem.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It isn=E2=80=99t just Na=
sdaq. Another exchange operator, IEX Group Inc., said in March that it woul=
d stop accepting investors=E2=80=99 orders in Class A shares of Berkshire H=
athaway =E2=80=9Cdue to an internal price limitation within the trading sys=
tem.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s the =
trouble: Nasdaq and some other market operators record stock prices in a co=
mpact computer format that uses 32 bits, or ones and zeros. The biggest num=
ber possible is two to the 32nd power minus one, or 4,294,967,295. Stock pr=
ices are frequently stored using four decimal places, so the highest possib=
le price is $429,496.7295.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No other stock i=
s anywhere near Berkshire Class A=E2=80=99s stratospheric price levels, so =
it is understandable why the engineers behind Nasdaq=E2=80=99s and IEX=E2=
=80=99s systems chose the number format, which programmers call a four-byte=
 unsigned integer.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When I firs=
t read the headline (=E2=80=9CBerkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s Stock Price Is T=
oo Much for Computers=E2=80=9D) I assumed that this was a=C2=A0<em>signed=
=C2=A0</em>integer, and that if Berkshire=E2=80=99s price ever ticked up to=
 $429,496.7296 it would roll over to be some enormous negative number in th=
e exchanges=E2=80=99 computer systems. And then if you put in a market orde=
r to sell Berkshire when you saw it trading at $429,496.70, it would take a=
 second to get a fill, and in that second the price would tick over to=C2=
=A0like negative $429,400, and the exchange would say =E2=80=9Cokay we have=
 taken away your Berkshire share and you owe us $429,400,=E2=80=9D and oops=
 oops oops.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, no, unsigned. I guess it r=
olls over to zero? Also great fun. =E2=80=9CWow, Berkshire is really going =
up, I should sell,=E2=80=9D you think, as it hits $429,495, and then by the=
 time your order goes in it has rolled over and you sell for two cents. Too=
 slow! Honestly the stock market should work like that. Stock prices get to=
o high and just start over at zero. Keep things interesting.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">My model for the last year or so in the capital markets h=
as been =E2=80=9Ceverything keeps getting a little dumber each day,=E2=80=
=9D but what if this story is actually the better model? What if the correc=
t model is something like =E2=80=9Ccapital markets kept getting more and mo=
re perfect until they reached maximum perfection sometime in=C2=A02020 and =
then, due to a glitch in the number formatting, flipped over into absolute =
nonsense=E2=80=9D?</p>
