<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">The Theranos defense=C2=A0</h2><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Public and private companies are subject to different rules abo=
ut what they have to disclose to their shareholders, but the basic rule of =
securities fraud is the same. You are not allowed to knowingly make an untr=
ue statement about a material fact to investors to try to get them to buy s=
tock.[1] You can=E2=80=99t lie about your company to get people to give you=
 money. Reasonable enough.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice, thi=
s basic rule is=C2=A0<em>vastly=C2=A0</em>more likely to be enforced agains=
t public companies than it is against private, venture-backed startups. One=
 main reason for this is that public companies make their statements public=
ly, to everyone, and everyone can buy their stock. If a public company exec=
utive says =E2=80=9Cwe had a good quarter=E2=80=9D in a magazine interview,=
 people will go buy the stock on the stock exchange; if it turns out she wa=
s lying, they will all have been deceived about a material fact in connecti=
on with a securities trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a private co=
mpany executive says =E2=80=9Cwe had a good quarter=E2=80=9D in a magazine =
interview, readers might say =E2=80=9Coh interesting, nice to hear good new=
s out of a startup,=E2=80=9D but they will not go buy the stock, because th=
ere=E2=80=99s no stock for sale and nowhere to buy it. Investors can only b=
uy the stock from the private company itself, in occasional, carefully cont=
rolled and lawyered fundraising rounds. When the company is raising a round=
, it will put together disclosure documents and send them to potential inve=
stors, and when it sells stock to those investors it will make them sign a =
contract saying in effect that they=E2=80=99ve done their due diligence, th=
at they=E2=80=99re only relying on the company=E2=80=99s official disclosur=
e, and that they=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t sue the company for lying in a random m=
agazine interview.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The approximate result i=
s that=C2=A0<em>every=C2=A0</em>untrue public statement made by a public co=
mpany has securities-fraud victims,[2] while almost no untrue public statem=
ents by private companies have securities-fraud victims.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A related reason is that, when public companies=C2=A0s=
ell stock, their disclosure documents are public; when private companies se=
ll stock, their disclosure documents are private, sent only to potential in=
vestors with =E2=80=9CCONFIDENTIAL=E2=80=9D stamped on the cover. If a regu=
lator or journalist or plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyer or concerned citizen want=
s to spend an hour checking out a public company=E2=80=99s disclosure to se=
e if it has any lies, the disclosure is easily available on the internet. Y=
ou cannot idly check out the disclosure documents that startups send to pot=
ential investors, so they just get a lot less scrutiny from outside enforce=
rs.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third reason is that the audiences ar=
e different. When a public company says something untrue, there are lots of=
 victims (who buy stock). Some of them will be recruited by plaintiffs=E2=
=80=99 lawyers (who monitor public companies=E2=80=99 disclosures, looking =
for lies) to sue. Others will just be sympathetic victims; the Securities a=
nd Exchange Commission or federal prosecutors will bring a fraud case and t=
alk about how the company has deceived ordinary investors.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">When a private startup says something untrue, even in conne=
ction with a sale of stock, the victims will often be sophisticated venture=
 capital firms.[3] These firms are less likely to sue, for a couple of reas=
ons. For one thing, they want to invest in other startups, so they want to =
cultivate a reputation for being founder-friendly, and suing founders for f=
raud is not friendly. For another thing, they want to raise money from pens=
ions and endowments and allocators, so they want to cultivate a reputation =
for being smart and doing good due diligence; calling attention to how they=
 got tricked is not helpful. For a third thing, they are looking, in their =
venture capital investments, for high-risk, high-reward bets. The ideal fou=
nder, for them, is someone who promises the impossible and then delivers it=
. If a founder promises the impossible and then does not deliver it, well, =
you know, that=E2=80=99s okay, most startups fail.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Similarly, prosecutors and regulators are less likely to bring a ca=
se in those circumstances: If the victims have no real complaints, it is ha=
rder to get a jury to punish the fraud.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 result of all of this is that there is, I think, a norm that a bit more =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0stretching of the truth =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is tolerated in ventu=
re-backed startups than in public companies. Tolerated by the SEC, by prose=
cutors, by venture investors, by startup founders themselves. <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23761771.258996/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjYvc3RhcnR1cHMtc29tZX=
RpbWVzLXN0cmV0Y2gtdGhlLXRydXRo/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9fe1fdd1" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I wrote in Februa=
ry</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=C2=A0is, like, sta=
rtups, man. What you want, when you invest in a startup, is a founder who c=
ombines (1) an insanely ambitious vision with (2) a clear-eyed plan to make=
 it come true=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>(3) the ability to make people believe=
 in the vision=C2=A0<em>now</em>. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll tinker with hydrog=
en for a while=C2=A0and maybe in a decade or so a fuel-cell-powered truck w=
ill come out of it=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0<em>True</em>, yes, but a bad=C2=A0<em>pi=
tch</em>. The=C2=A0<em>pitch=C2=A0</em>is, like, you=C2=A0put your arm arou=
nd the shoulder of an investor, you gesture sweepingly into the distance, y=
ou close your eyes, she closes her eyes, and you say in=C2=A0mellifluous to=
nes: =E2=80=9CCan=E2=80=99t you see the trucks rolling off the assembly lin=
e right now? Aren=E2=80=99t they beautiful? So clean and efficient, look at=
 how nicely they drive, look at all those components, all built in-house, a=
ren=E2=80=99t they=C2=A0amazing? Here, hold out your hand, you can=C2=A0<em=
>touch=C2=A0</em>the truck right now. Let=E2=80=99s go for a drive.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s not<em>=C2=A0true</em>, but it=E2=80=99s a nice=C2=
=A0<em>metaphor</em>; the goal is to get the investor to see the future, so=
 she=E2=80=99ll give you money today, so that you can build the future tomo=
rrow.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this norm is not wri=
tten in the law anywhere, and it doesn=E2=80=99t entirely correspond to leg=
al concepts. (Perhaps you could express it in terms of =E2=80=9Cmateriality=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Creliance=E2=80=9D; like, private investors don=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0<em>believe=C2=A0</em>or=C2=A0<em>care about=C2=A0</em>startups=
=E2=80=99 lies, so they don=E2=80=99t count as fraud?[4]) It's just, if a p=
ublic company lies a little bit, it will certainly be called on it; if a ve=
nture-backed startup lies a medium amount, it probably won=E2=80=99t.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One result is that when a venture-backed private=
 company=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>get in trouble for securities fraud, it pr=
obably won=E2=80=99t be=C2=A0<em>just=C2=A0</em>for securities fraud; it pr=
obably won=E2=80=99t be because its disappointed venture capital investors =
are sympathetic victims. It will probably be that the company is a high-pro=
file target for some other reason, and securities fraud is a good vehicle f=
or getting the company in trouble.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway h=
ere=E2=80=99s how <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
23761771.258996/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3MzYwLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy8xMzgxMzg1L2V4LXR=
oZXJhbm9zLWNlby1zLWRlZmVuc2UtZW1lcmdlcy1pbi1wcmUtdHJpYWwtYmF0dGxl/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBb6310e10" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">Elizabeth Holmes=E2=80=99s criminal case is going</a>:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Former Theranos CEO Elizabeth Holme=
s=E2=80=99 wire fraud defense surfaced Tuesday when her attorneys urged a C=
alifornia federal judge to allow jurors at her upcoming criminal fraud tria=
l to hear that exaggeration is part of Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s startup cul=
ture, while seeking to curb witness testimony on inaccurate blood tests and=
 bypassed regulations.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The two=
 points here are:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 4=
0px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Uh, yeah, at som=
e level, exaggeration is part of Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s startup culture, =
and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People are not mainly angry at=
 Elizabeth Holmes because she raised a bunch of money from rich venture cap=
italists to fund her blood-testing startup by making overly optimistic clai=
